# Optional Chaining (`?.`) in JavaScript

## Introduction

Optional Chaining (`?.`) JavaScript ka ek feature hai jo nested objects ki properties ko safely access karne deta hai.

Agar koi property exist nahi karti to error dene ke bajaye `undefined` return karta hai.

---

# Problem Without Optional Chaining

```js
const product = {
    name: "Nike Bag"
};

console.log(product.image.data);
```

### Output

```txt
TypeError: Cannot read properties of undefined (reading 'data')
```

### Reason

```js
product.image
```

`undefined` hai aur JavaScript:

```js
undefined.data
```

access nahi kar sakta.

---

# Solution Using Optional Chaining

```js
const product = {
    name: "Nike Bag"
};

console.log(product.image?.data);
```

### Output

```txt
undefined
```

Error nahi aayega.

---

# How It Works

```js
product.image?.data
```

Internally JavaScript kuch aisa karta hai:

```js
if(product.image === null || product.image === undefined){
    return undefined;
}
else{
    return product.image.data;
}
```

---

# Real World Example

## Product With Image

```js
const product1 = {
    name: "Nike Bag",
    image: {
        data: "buffer-data",
        contentType: "image/png"
    }
};

console.log(product1.image?.data);
```

### Output

```txt
buffer-data
```

---

## Product Without Image

```js
const product2 = {
    name: "Adidas Bag"
};

console.log(product2.image?.data);
```

### Output

```txt
undefined
```

